\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 11 Problem Two
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
2.
 Consider the series 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(x+2)^{n}}{n2^{n}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Determine the radius and interval of convergence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the Ratio Test:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bigg|\frac{\frac{(x+2)^{n+1}}{(n+1)(2^{n+1})}}{\frac{(x+2)^{n}}{n2^{n}}}\bigg|=|\frac{(x+2)^{n+1}}{(x+2)^{n}}|\times\frac{n}{n+1}\times\frac{2^{n}}{2^{n+1}}\implies\frac{1}{2}|x+2|<1\implies|x+2|<2\implies-2<x+2<2=-4<x<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the radius of convergence is 2.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we check the endpoints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-4$
\end_inset

 the original series equals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(-2)^{n}}{n2^{n}}=\Sigma\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(-1)^{n}2^{n}}{n2^{n}}=\Sigma\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(-1)^{n}}{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By this form we know that when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

is even then the whole term will be negative because of 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{n+1}$
\end_inset

; however, the whole term will be negative also when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

is odd because of 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore this series is the equivalent of the negative Harmonic Series,
 which we know to be divergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 the original series equals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\frac{(-1)^{n+1}2^{n}}{n2^{n}}$
\end_inset

, which is the Alternative Harmonic series, which we know to be convergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the interval of convergence is 
\begin_inset Formula $(-4,0].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) For what values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 does the series converge absolutely?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The series converges absolutely for the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-4,0]$
\end_inset

 because within that interval the term 
\begin_inset Formula $|(x+2)^{n}|<2^{n}$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 becomes the dominant term in the fraction, which because it is in the denominat
or, causes the entire series to converge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(c) For what values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 does the series converge conditionally?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The series converges conditionally only for the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, as was tested when we were determining the interval of convergence.
 Conditional convergence basically states that the series (at a particular
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 value) converges only if there is an alternating term 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{n}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_body
